1. Planting in colder conditions may slow down seed germination.
2. Some plants may be more susceptible to pests or diseases in warmer temperatures.
3. Colder temperatures may help prevent weeds from competing with the plants.
4. The risk of overwatering is lower in colder conditions.
5. Some plants may require a period of cold stratification to germinate properly.
6. Warmer temperatures may cause the soil to dry out faster.
7. Planting in colder conditions may reduce the risk of transplant shock.